                <p dir=3D"ltr"><span>A set is simply a collection of distin=
ct objects. These objects can be numbers, letters, or even people=E2=80=94a=
nything! We denote a set using curly brackets.</span><br><b><strong>For exa=
mple: </strong></b><span>A =3D {1, 2, 3}</span></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"lt=
r"><span>Set Operations can be defined as&nbsp;the operations performed on =
two or more sets to obtain a single set containing a combination of element=
s from all the sets being operated upon. </span></p></blockquote><figure cl=
ass=3D"image"><img src=3D"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/upload=
s/20240619161350/Set-Operations.webp" alt=3D"Set-Operations" width=3D"1000"=
 height=3D"470"><figcaption>Set Operations</figcaption></figure><ul><li val=
ue=3D"1"><span>Set operations are mathematical operations performed on sets=
, which are collections of distinct objects or elements</span><b><strong>. =
</strong></b></li><li value=3D"2"><span>There are three major types of oper=
ation on sets: Union (=E2=88=AA), Intersection (=E2=88=A9), and Difference =
(-). </span><br><span>Other operations include Complement, Symmetric Differ=
ence, Addition, and Subtraction.</span></li></ul><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>The m=
ost common set operations, such as union, intersection, disjoint, set diffe=
rence, etc., will be explored in detail below, including their definitions,=
 examples, and Venn diagrams.</span></p><h2 id=3D"union-of-sets" style=3D"t=
ext-align:left"><b><strong>Union of Sets</strong></b></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><s=
pan>The </span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/union-of-sets=
/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><b><strong>Union of sets</strong></b>=
</a><span> A and B, denoted by </span><b><strong>A =E2=88=AA B, </strong></=
b><span>is the set of distinct elements that belong to set A or set B, or b=
oth. This operation can be represented as; </span></p><blockquote><p dir=3D=
"ltr"><span>A =E2=88=AA B =3D {x: x =E2=88=88 A or x =E2=88=88 B}</span></p=
></blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>In simple terms, the union includes ever=
y element that appears in either of the two sets, without any repetition. W=
here x represents an element that belongs to A or B (or both).</span></p><h=
3 id=3D"venn-diagram-of-a-u-b" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Venn Diagram=
 For </span><b><strong>Union of Sets</strong></b></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>=
The area shaded in green represents A =E2=88=AA B or the union of sets A an=
d B.</span></p><div id=3D"GFG_AD_Desktop_InContent_ATF_728x280" style=3D"te=
xt-align: center; margin: 10px 0px;"></div><figure class=3D"image"><img src=
=3D"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250411172445078226=
/unit_u_495.webp" alt=3D"unit_u_495" width=3D"400" height=3D"350" loading=
=3D"lazy"><figcaption>Venn diagram of A =E2=88=AA B</figcaption></figure><p=
 dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>Example: </strong></b><span>Find the union of A =3D=
 {2, 3, 4} and B =3D {3, 4, 5}.</span><br><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b=
></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>A =E2=88=AA B =3D {2, 3, 4, 5}.</span=
></p></blockquote><h2 id=3D"intersection" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><str=
ong>Intersection</strong></b></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>The</span><a href=3D=
"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/intersection-of-sets/" target=3D"_blan=
k" rel=3D"noopener"><span> intersection of the sets</span></a><span> A and =
B, denoted by</span><b><strong> A =E2=88=A9 B,</strong></b><span> is the se=
t of elements that belong to both A and B, i.e. set of the common elements =
in A and B. This operation is represented as: </span></p><blockquote><p dir=
=3D"ltr"><span>A=E2=88=A9B =3D {x: x =E2=88=88 A&nbsp;and&nbsp;x =E2=88=88 =
B}</span></p></blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><br><span>In other words, the inte=
rsection contains only those elements that are present in both sets. Here, =
x represents the elements that are common to both sets A and B.</span></p><=
h3 id=3D"venn-diagram-of-a-b" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Venn Diagram =
For Intersection of Sets</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>The area shaded in=
 green represents A=E2=88=A9B or the intersection of sets A and B, which in=
cludes the elements common to both sets A and B.</span></p><figure class=3D=
"image"><img src=3D"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/2025=
0411172535654131/uni495.webp" alt=3D"uni495" width=3D"400" height=3D"350" l=
oading=3D"lazy"><figcaption>Venn diagram of A =E2=88=A9 B</figcaption></fig=
ure><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: left;"><b><strong>Example: </strong=
></b><span>Find the intersection of A =3D {2, 3, 4} and B =3D {3, 4, 5}</sp=
an></p><div id=3D"GFG_AD_Incontent_2" style=3D"text-align: center; margin: =
10px 0px;"></div><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b></p><block=
quote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Look for elements that are common to both sets A=
 and B.</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>A =E2=88=A9 B =3D {3, 4}.</span></p>=
</blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><span>The intersec=
tion of sets A and B can also be interpreted as:</span></p><blockquote><p d=
ir=3D"ltr"><span>n (A =E2=88=A9B) =3D n (A) + n (B) =E2=80=93 n (A=E2=88=AA=
B)</span></p></blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><span=
>Where,</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>n(A) =3D the cardinality (or nu=
mber of elements) of set A,</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>n(B) =3D the c=
ardinality of set B,</span></li><li value=3D"3"><span>n(A=E2=88=AAB) =3D th=
e cardinality of the union of sets A and B.</span></li></ul><h2 id=3D"disjo=
int" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Disjoint Set</strong></b></h2><p =
dir=3D"ltr"><span>Two sets are said to be </span><a href=3D"https://www.gee=
ksforgeeks.org/maths/disjoint-sets/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><sp=
an>disjoint</span></a><span> if their intersection is the </span><a href=3D=
"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/empty-set/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"n=
oopener"><span>empty set</span></a><span>. i.e., sets have no common elemen=
ts. In simpler terms, they don=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Coverlap=E2=80=9D at all.<=
/span><br><span> So if you try to find their intersection, you=E2=80=99ll g=
et the empty set, which we denote by the symbol =CF=95 or {}.</span></p><h3=
 id=3D"venn-diagram-of-a-disjoint-b" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Venn D=
iagram For </span><b><strong>Disjoint Set</strong></b><span>s</span></h3><p=
 dir=3D"ltr"><span>The sets A and B are disjoint, meaning they have no comm=
on elements (no overlap).</span></p><figure class=3D"image"><img src=3D"htt=
ps://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250411172707663120/6757.w=
ebp" alt=3D"6757" width=3D"400" height=3D"350" loading=3D"lazy"><figcaption=
>Venn Diagram of A Disjoint B</figcaption></figure><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><stron=
g>For Example: </strong></b><span>Let A =3D {1, 3, 5, 7, 9} and B =3D {2, 4=
, 6, 8} </span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b></p><blo=
ckquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>A and B are disjoint sets since both of them h=
ave no common elements.</span></p></blockquote><h2 id=3D"set-difference" st=
yle=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Set Difference</strong></b><span>&nbsp;<=
/span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>The difference between sets is denoted by</=
span><b><strong> 'A - B'</strong></b><span>, which is the set containing el=
ements that are in A but not in B i.e., all elements of A except the elemen=
t of B.</span></p><h3 id=3D"venn-diagram-of-a-b-1" style=3D"text-align:left=
"><span>Venn Diagram For </span><b><strong>Set Difference</strong></b></h3>=
<p dir=3D"ltr"><span>In the below diagram, the </span><a href=3D"https://ww=
w.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/difference-of-sets/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noo=
pener"><span>set difference</span></a><span> A=E2=88=92B contains all the e=
lements that are in A but not in B.</span></p><figure class=3D"image"><img =
src=3D"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250411172924735=
560/file.webp" alt=3D"file" width=3D"400" height=3D"350" loading=3D"lazy"><=
figcaption>Venn diagram A-B</figcaption></figure><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>=
Example: </strong></b><span>If A =3D {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} and B =3D {2, 4, 6, 8}=
, find A - B.</span><br><b><strong>Solution: </strong></b></p><blockquote><=
p dir=3D"ltr"><span>A - B =3D {1, 3, 5}</span></p></blockquote><p dir=3D"lt=
r"><span>We can also state that the difference between set A and set B is e=
quivalent to the intersection of set A with the complement of set B. Theref=
ore,</span></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>A =E2=88=92 B =3D A =E2=88=
=A9 B=E2=80=B2</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>where B=E2=80=B2 =3D the comp=
lement of set B.</span></p></blockquote><h2 id=3D"symmetric-difference" sty=
le=3D"text-align:left"><span>Symmetric Difference</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"=
><span>The</span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/symmetric-d=
ifference-of-sets/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><span> symmetric dif=
ference</span></a><span> of A and B includes elements in A or B but not bot=
h.</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>It is denoted by: A=E2=80=89=E2=96=
=B3=E2=80=89B or  A =E2=8A=95 B.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>The symme=
tric difference is like saying, =E2=80=9CGive me everything that=E2=80=99s =
not shared.</span></li><li value=3D"3"><span>It is defined as: A=E2=80=89=
=E2=96=B3=E2=80=89B =3D (A=E2=88=92B) =E2=88=AA (B=E2=88=92A)</span></li></=
ul><h3 id=3D"venn-diagram-for-symmetric-difference" style=3D"text-align:lef=
t"><span>Venn Diagram For Symmetric Difference</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><s=
pan>The symmetric difference A=CE=94B includes elements that are in either =
A or B but not in both.</span></p><figure class=3D"image"><img src=3D"https=
://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250411174157863278/t_u_495.=
webp" alt=3D"t_u_495" width=3D"400" height=3D"270" loading=3D"lazy"><figcap=
tion>Venn Diagram of A =E2=96=B3=E2=80=89B</figcaption></figure><p dir=3D"l=
tr"><b><strong>Example</strong></b><span>: Let set A =3D {1, 2, 3},  and se=
t B =3D {3, 4, 5}, then Find the symmetric difference </span></p><p dir=3D"=
ltr"><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>=
 A =E2=96=B3 B =3D {1, 2, 4, 5}</span></p></blockquote><h2 id=3D"complement=
-of-a-set" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Complement of a Set</span></h2><=
p dir=3D"ltr"><span>If U is a universal set and X is any subset of U, then =
the complement of X consists of all the elements in U that are not in X.</s=
pan></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>X</span><sup><span>' </span></sup><span>=3D {a=
 : a=E2=88=88 U&nbsp;and&nbsp;x =E2=88=89 A}</span></p><h3 id=3D"venn-diagr=
am-for-complement-of-a-set" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Venn Diagram Fo=
r Complement of a Set</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>In the diagram below,=
 set A</span><sup><span>'</span></sup><span> includes all elements not in A=
, relative to the universal set.</span></p><figure class=3D"image"><img src=
=3D"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250411173142259586=
/76.webp" alt=3D"76" width=3D"400" height=3D"350" loading=3D"lazy"><figcapt=
ion>Complement of a Set</figcaption></figure><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>Exam=
ple: </strong></b><span>Let U =3D {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8} And A =3D {1, 2,=
 5, 6}</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b></p><block=
quote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Then, the </span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksfor=
geeks.org/maths/complement-of-a-set/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><s=
pan>complement</span></a><span> of A, denoted as A=E2=80=B2, will be: A=E2=
=80=B2 =3D {3, 4, 7, 8}</span></p></blockquote><h2 id=3D"addition-and-subtr=
action" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Addition and Subtraction</stro=
ng></b><span>&nbsp;</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>The addition of sets A =
and B, known as Minkowski addition, results in a new set where each element=
 is the sum of every possible pair of elements, one from set A and one from=
 set B. </span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>In other words, the new set contain=
s all possible sums of elements taken from the two sets. Set subtraction op=
erates similarly but involves subtracting each element of set B from each e=
lement of set A. These operations are only meaningful when applied to numer=
ic data types; if applied otherwise, they become symbolic with no practical=
 significance.</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Additionally, set addition is=
 commutative, meaning the order of the sets does not affect the result. How=
ever, set subtraction is not commutative, as the order of the sets does aff=
ect the outcome.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>n (A =E2=88=AA =
B) =3D n(A) + n(B) - n (A =E2=88=A9 B)</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"te=
xt-align: left;"><span>A - B =3D A =E2=88=A9 B' </span></p></blockquote><h2=
 id=3D"property-of-set-operation" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Propertie=
s of Set Operations</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Set operations have sev=
eral important properties that govern their behavior. Here are some fundame=
ntal properties of set operations:</span></p><h3 id=3D"closure-property" st=
yle=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Closure Property</strong></b></h3><ul><l=
i value=3D"1"><span>Set operations are closed under their respective operat=
ions, meaning that operating on sets results in another set. </span></li><l=
i value=3D"2"><span>For example, the union, intersection, and difference of=
 sets always produce sets as their results.</span></li></ul><h3 id=3D"commu=
tative-property" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Commutative Property<=
/strong></b></h3><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>Union: A =E2=88=AA B =3D B =E2=
=88=AA A</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>Intersection: A =E2=88=A9 B =3D B=
 =E2=88=A9 A</span></li><li value=3D"3"><span>Symmetric Difference: A =CE=
=94 B =3D B =CE=94 A</span></li></ul><h3 id=3D"associative-property" style=
=3D"text-align:left"><span>Associative Property</span></h3><ul><li value=3D=
"1"><span>Union: (A =E2=88=AA B) =E2=88=AA C =3D A =E2=88=AA (B =E2=88=AA C=
)</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>Intersection: (A =E2=88=A9 B) =E2=88=A9 =
C =3D A =E2=88=A9 (B =E2=88=A9 C)</span></li></ul><h3 id=3D"distributive-pr=
operty" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Distributive Property</span></h3><u=
l><li value=3D"1"><span>Union over Intersection: A =E2=88=AA (B =E2=88=A9 C=
